HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 975
By Jones J
A RESOLUTION to honor and commend Gloria McKissack of
Nashville.
WHEREAS, it is our privilege to honor an iconic veteran of the Civil Rights Movement
who has worked tirelessly to advance racial justice in Tennessee and across our nation; and
WHEREAS, such an esteemed individual is Gloria McKissack of Nashville, a veteran
civil rights activist, educator, and lifelong advocate for justice whose faith has been lived out
through courageous action; and
WHEREAS, born in Detroit, Michigan, on August 31, 1943, Gloria McKissack graduated
from Central High School before deciding to enroll at a southern HBCU (Historically Black
Colleges and Universities), Tennessee A&I College, now Tennessee State University, instead of
accepting a scholarship to Wayne State University, which was then predominantly white; and
WHEREAS, as a student at Tennessee State University, she participated in the
Nashville Sit-In Movement and joined SNCC, the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee,
risking her life to dismantle segregation; and
WHEREAS, at that time, in 1960, the Freedom Rides had taken place, and Greensboro,
North Carolina, had started a sit-in movement; Gloria McKissack almost immediately became an
active participant in the Nashville Sit-In Movement, and she did not hesitate when recruited by
expelled Freedom Riders to join the Student Non-Violent Coordinating Committee; and
WHEREAS, SNCC students, under the leadership of future Congressman John Lewis,
risked their education and their lives to end discrimination, not only at lunch counters but
restaurants, hotels, public parks, theaters, and places of employment; and
WHEREAS, Ms. McKissack still suffers from a back injury that she incurred when a brick
was thrown at her and others seeking safety at First Baptist Church, Capitol Hill; and
HJR0975
013544
- 1 -

WHEREAS, a lifelong educator and activist, Gloria McKissack continues to share her
firsthand experiences from the Civil Rights Movement, her early days as an instructor as
schools were being integrated, and the features of today's movement that give her hope for the
future; and
WHEREAS, it is most appropriate that we pay respectful tribute to this trailblazing hero
of the Civil Rights Movement in Tennessee and our nation; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor and commend Gloria McKissack, an outstanding and
inspirational leader for social justice and human rights, for her unwavering commitment to
nonviolence and her lifelong service to our State and our country.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
